ble for all. He considers the various ways individuals cultivate distraction and hope for future mobility: education, migration, consumption, and prayer. These hope-filled practices are a form of emotional labor for young men, placing responsibility on the individual rather than structural issues in Egypt's economy. Illuminating this emotional labor, Pettit shows how the capitalist economy continues to capture the attention of the very people harmed by it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalismzEgypt2DLC. 0aCapitalismzEgypt. 0aHopexSocial aspectszEgypt2DLC. 0aHopexSocial aspectszEgypt. 0aMiddle classzEgypt2DLC. 0aMiddle classzEgypt. 0aPrecarious employmentzEgypt2DLC. 0aPrecarious employmentzEgypt. 0aUnderemploymentzEgypt2DLC. 0aUnderemploymentzEgypt. 0aYoung menxEmploymentzEgypt2DLC. 0aYoung menxEmploymentzEgypt. 0aYoung menzEgyptxSocial conditions2DLC. 0aYoung menzEgyptxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh  aEgypt.  adisconnection.  adistraction.  aemotion.  ahope.  alabor.  amasculinity.  ameritocracy.  amiddle class.  aprecarity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363745040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637450/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles